# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] A presidential election was held in South Carolina on January 7, 1789, as part of the 1789 United States presidential election.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The state legislature chose 7 representatives, or electors to the Electoral College, who voted for President and Vice President.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-89-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina, which became the 8th state on May 23, 1788, unanimously cast its seven electoral votes for George Washington during its first presidential election.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The **1788 United States House of Representatives elections in South Carolina** were held on November 24 and 25, 1788 to select five Representatives for two-year terms from the state of South Carolina.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The elections resulted in two candidates in support of Washington's administration and three candidates opposed to his policies.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Smith defeated two candidates in the first election of the 1st congressional district, known as the Charleston District.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Aedanus Burke defeated Robert Barnwell in the first election of the 2nd congressional district, known as the Beaufort-Orangeburg District.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Daniel Huger won the first election of the 3rd congressional district, known as the Georgetown-Cheraw District.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Thomas Sumter won the first election of the 4th congressional district, known as the Camden District.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Thomas Tudor Tucker won the first election of the 5th congressional district, known as the Ninety-Six District.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The **1788–1789 United States Senate elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senate elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] As these elections were prior to the ratification of the Seventeenth Amendment in 1913, senators were chosen by state legislatures.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senators were elected over a wide range of time throughout 1788 and 1789.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Pennsylvania was the first state to select its senators on September 30, 1788, and South Carolina was the last state on January 22, 1789.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] New York, North Carolina, and Rhode Island elected their senators between July 16, 1789, and June 12, 1790, after the convening of Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Among the original 13 states, ten of them selected their senators prior to the official start of the 1st United States Congress on March 4, 1789, ranging from Pennsylvania in September 1788 to South Carolina in January 1789.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] New York failed to elect its senators until July 1789.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began; North Carolina then elected its senators in November 1789, but Rhode Island failed to ratify the Constitution until 1790.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Under Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Constitution, the actual division of the Senate's seats into the three classes was not performed until after the 1st Congress convened.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Thus, the 20 elected senators from the ten initial states did not know ahead of time whether they would serve Class 1's interim two-year term, Class 2's interim four-year term, or the full six-year term of Class 3.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Then starting with New York, a random draw determined which classes each new state's seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Among the initial 20 senators elected before the 1st Congress began on March 4, 1789, 13 of them were Pro-Administration.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] New York failed to elect its senators until after the Congress began, so its seats are labelled here as "Vacant." North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the Congress began, so their seats are not included here.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Article I, Section 3, Clause 2 of the U.S.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The allocation of the classes by lot then took place in May 1789, two months after the first Congress began in March 1789.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] New York was then the first to be treated as a "new state admitted to the Union" under this process when they elected their senators in July 1789, drawing lots to determine which classes their seats would belong to while keeping the three classes as close to the same size as possible.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] In these general elections, the winners were elected in advance of March 4, 1789, the date set to be the beginning of the 1st Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Ordered by state, then by the class that they were eventually assigned in May 1789.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] In these general elections, the winners were elected in 1789 after March 4; ordered by election date.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The Maryland General Assembly convened on December 10, 1788, in order to vote for the inaugural holders of Maryland's seats.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] There were two candidates for each seat, and all four were of the Federalist Party.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] An outright majority (50% plus one) was required for a candidate to win.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Charles Carroll won election over Uriah Forrest by a margin of 3.70%, or 3 votes, for one of the seats.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] This election was decided on the third ballot, after the first did not produce a majority and the second had both candidates tie.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] John Henry won election over George Gale by a margin of 2.44%, or 2 votes, for the other seat.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] This election was decided on the second ballot, after both candidates tied with pluralities on the first.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] In May 1789, the lot draw performed by the 1st U.S.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senate assigned Carroll's seat to Class 1, whose term would expire March 3, 1791, and Henry's seat to Class 3, whose term would expire March 3, 1795.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] It was the first such election, and before the actual election the New York State Legislature had to establish rules for proceeding.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] They decided to ballot separately, and then pass a joint resolution once they had concurred in the election of two candidates.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On July 15, Schuyler was nominated first, and members of each chamber attempted to substitute the names of other candidates, including Ezra L'Hommedieu and Rufus King.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] These motions failed, and Schuyler was elected by a vote of 37 to 19 in the Assembly, and 13 to 6 in the Senate.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] King's election came after individual legislators and the two chambers failed to agree on the election of James Duane, Ezra L'Hommedieu, or Lewis Morris.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] King was then elected unanimously by the Assembly, and by a vote of 11 to 8 in the Senate.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On July 16, Schuyler and King were appointed to the U.S.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senate by a joint resolution of the State Legislature.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] King took his seat on July 25, and drew the lot for Class 3, his term expiring on March 3, 1795.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Schuyler took his seat on July 27, and drew the lot for Class 1, his term expiring on March 3, 1791.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The 1st United States Congress convened at New York City, as did the regular session of the New York State Legislature in January 1790.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Schuyler retained his seat in the State Senate while serving concurrently in the U.S.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Schuyler was also elected on January 15 a member of the State's Council of Appointments which consisted of the Governor of New York, and four State Senators elected annually by the State Assembly.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On January 27, the New York State Legislature resolved that it was "incompatible with the U.S.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Constitution for any person holding an office under the United States government at the same time to have a seat in the Legislature of this State", and that if a member of the State Legislature was elected or appointed to a federal office, the seat should be declared vacant upon acceptance.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senator Schuyler, Federal Judge James Duane and Congressmen John Hathorn and John Laurance vacated their seats in the State Senate.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On April 3, John Cantine, a member of the Council of Appointments, raised the question if Schuyler, after vacating his State Senate seat, was still a member of the council.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Philip Livingston, another member, held that once elected a member could not be expelled in any case.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] On April 5, Governor Clinton asked the State Assembly for a decision, but the latter refused to do so, arguing that it was a question of law, which could be pursued in the courts.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Schuyler thus kept his seat in the Council of Appointments until the end of the term.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] North Carolina was the 12th state to ratify the new United States Constitution, doing so in November 1789, months after the First Congress had first convened.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] A few days after that ratification, on November 26, 1789, the two houses of the state legislature jointly elected incumbent Governor Samuel Johnston (who was considered pro-Administration) as North Carolina's first United States Senator.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The minutes of the state Senate indicate that the two houses had actually voted for both U.S.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Senate seats, but that no candidate received a majority for the second seat.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Days later, the state Senate sent messages to the state House of Commons nominating candidates for the state's other Senate seat.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] These included William Lenoir, William Blount, Benjamin Hawkins, and Timothy Bloodworth.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Hawkins (who was also pro-Administration at the time) was elected jointly by the two houses on December 8, 1789.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The election was held on September 30, 1788.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] The Pennsylvania General Assembly, consisting of the House of Representatives and the Senate, elected Pennsylvania's first two United States senators, William Maclay and Robert Morris.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1789-united-states-senate-elections-in-south-carolina] Anti-Federalist William Maclay was elected to the two-year staggered term of the Class 1 seat, while Federalist and founding father Robert Morris was elected to the full six-year term of the Class 3 seat.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The **1790–91 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between April 27, 1790, and October 11, 1791.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before or after the first session of the 2nd United States Congress convened on October 24, 1791.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] This was the first midterm election cycle, which took place in the middle of President George Washington's first term.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The size of the House increased to 67 seats after the new state of Vermont elected its first representatives.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] While formal political parties still did not exist, coalitions of pro-Washington (Pro-Admin.) representatives and anti-Administration representatives each gained two seats as a result of the addition of new states to the union.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Speaker Frederick Muhlenberg was succeeded by Jonathan Trumbull Jr., who became the 2nd Speaker of the House.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Either five or six incumbents did not seek re-election.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Aedanus Burke, a U.S. representative from South Carolina's 2nd congressional district, either retired or lost re-election but it is not known.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Pennsylvania at-large: Henry Wynkoop retired.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Pennsylvania at-large: Thomas Scott retired.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] In this period, each state fixed its own date for congressional general elections, as early as April 27, 1790 (in New York) and as late as October 11, 1791 (in Pennsylvania).
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Elections to a Congress took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when the Congress convened.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The first session of this Congress was convened in Philadelphia on October 24, 1791.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Kentucky and Vermont became states during the 2nd Congress, adding two seats each.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The legislation admitted Vermont was passed at the end of the 1st Congress taking effect on March 4, 1791, the first day of the 2nd Congress, so that Vermont was represented from the start of the Congress, while Kentucky was unrepresented until the 2nd session.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] There were special elections in 1790 and 1791 during the 1st United States Congress and 2nd United States Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] New states and newly ratified states are not included as special elections.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Elections are sorted by date then district.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Connecticut elected all five of its representatives at-large on a general ticket on September 20, 1790.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] There were two subsequent special elections.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The first was held to fill the vacancy left by Pierpont Edwards (Pro-Admin.) declining to serve and was won by Jeremiah Wadsworth (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The second was held September 19, 1791, to fill the vacancy left by Roger Sherman (Pro-Admin.)'s election to the Senate and was won by Amasa Learned (Pro-Admin.).
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Georgia switched to a conventional district system for the Second Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] At the time, the districts were not numbered, but are retroactively renumbered as the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd respectively here.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Kentucky was admitted during the 2nd Congress and elected its first representatives in 1792.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] In Maryland, two local factions briefly emerged, the Chesapeake and Potomac (or Potowmack) "parties".
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The Potomac faction, consisting of individuals from the small counties of southern Maryland and the Eastern Shore, aimed to maintain their status by curbing the increasing influence of the city of Baltimore and the more populous counties.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] To do so, they supported the development of the federal city and a canal on the Potomac River to secure their economic future.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Conversely, the Chesapeake faction advocated for Baltimore's growth.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Their strategy involved improving the Susquehanna River to channel the lucrative wheat trade from western Maryland and Pennsylvania through Baltimore.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] They also believed that political representation should reflect population growth patterns rather than be defined by the counties.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] They feared that a canal on the Potomac River would undermine Baltimore's prosperity by diverting trade to competitors like Georgetown, the proposed federal city, and Alexandria.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Temporarily setting aside differences at the national level, the "Chesapeake Ticket" was formed to punish incumbents who had supported the Potomac location for the proposed federal city.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] A "Potomac Ticket" was organized and led by Governor Smallwood.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Turnout in Baltimore was around 99%, and almost every ballot was cast for the Chesapeake Ticket.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Statewide, the ticket won an overwhelming majority, securing all six seats.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] This victory threatened the county-based rural oligarchy, prompting the House of Delegates to transition from a mixed system to a district-based system on December 19, 1790.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Under this new system, all of Baltimore's votes would go to just one representative, Harford County was grouped with Kent and Cecil Counties, and Anne Arundel County was grouped with Prince George's County and Annapolis.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] With the base of the Chesapeake "party" split between three districts, the Chesapeake faction would disappear.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Massachusetts law required a majority for election.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] This condition was met in four of the eight districts, the remaining four required between 2 and 9 ballots for election.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, therefore the numbering here is retroactive.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] North Carolina ratified the Constitution November 21, 1789, and elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Due to the cession of North Carolina's trans-Appalachian territory to form the Southwest Territory, the territory of the old 5th district was lost.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] North Carolina retained the same number of Representatives, and so it redistricted for the Second Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Pennsylvania had elected its Representatives at-large in the 1st Congress, but switched to using districts in the 2nd Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Five incumbents ran for re-election, four of whom won, while three others retired leaving three open seats.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Two districts had no incumbents residing in them, while one (the 8th district) had a single representative who declined to run for re-election and one (the 2nd district) had three incumbents, only one of whom ran for re-election.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution May 29, 1790.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] It elected its representatives after admission.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Rhode Island held elections for the 2nd Congress on October 18, 1790, about six weeks after elections for the 1st Congress due to the state's late ratification of the Constitution.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Vermont was admitted at the end of the First Congress, with the admission taking effect at the start of the Second Congress.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Vermont was entitled to elect two representatives.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Vermont law at the time required a majority to win an office.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1790-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] In the 1st district, no candidate won a majority, necessitating a run-off.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] A presidential election was held in Connecticut between November 2 and December 5, 1792, as part of the 1792 United States presidential election.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] The state legislature chose nine members of the Electoral College, each of whom, under the provisions of the Constitution prior to the passage of the Twelfth Amendment, cast two votes for President.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-connecticut] Connecticut's nine electors each cast one vote for incumbent George Washington and one for incumbent Vice President John Adams.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware] A presidential election was held in Delaware between November 2 and December 5, 1792, as part of the 1792 United States presidential election.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware] The state legislature chose three members of the Electoral College, each of whom, under the provisions of the Constitution prior to the passage of the Twelfth Amendment, cast two votes for President.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-delaware] Delaware's three electors each cast one vote for the incumbent, George Washington, and one vote for John Adams, the incumbent Vice President.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] A presidential election was held in South Carolina between November 2 and December 5, 1792, as part of the 1792 United States presidential election.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The state legislature chose eight members of the Electoral College, each of whom, under the provisions of the Constitution prior to the passage of the Twelfth Amendment, cast two votes for President.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina's eight electors each cast one vote for the incumbent, George Washington; with one exception, each of those electors cast a second vote for Vice President John Adams, the outlier voting for Aaron Burr.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The Federalist Party dominated South Carolina in the 1790s as it could count a number of prominent lowcountry planters among their ranks.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Many South Carolinians played important roles for the Federalist Party at the national level.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] The Jeffersonian-Republicans, however, were rising in prominence, especially as Charles Cotesworth Pinckney and Pierce Butler, both of whom signed the Constitution for South Carolina, joined the rival party.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] Although the Federalists dominated the state until 1800, by 1804 there were no Federalists in power.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina] South Carolina would remain a one-party state until the start of the Civil War.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Presidential elections were held in the United States from November 2 to December 5, 1792.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Incumbent President George Washington was elected to a second term by a unanimous vote in the electoral college, while John Adams was reelected as vice president.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was essentially unopposed, but Adams faced a competitive re-election against Governor George Clinton of New York.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Electoral rules of the time required each presidential elector to cast two votes without distinguishing which was for president and which for vice president.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The recipient of the most votes would then become president, and the runner-up vice president.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Democratic-Republican Party, which had organized in opposition to the policies of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Hamilton, supported Clinton for the position of vice president.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams, meanwhile, was backed by the Federalist Party in his bid for another term.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Neither party had fully organized, and partisan divisions had not yet solidified.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington received 132 electoral votes, one from each elector.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams won 77 electoral votes, enough to win re-election.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton finished in third place with 50 electoral votes, taking his home state of New York as well as three Southern states.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Two other candidates won the five remaining electoral votes.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] This election was the first in which each of the original 13 states appointed electors, as did the newly added states of Kentucky and Vermont.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In 1792, presidential elections were still conducted according to the original method established under the U.S.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Under this system, each elector cast two votes: the candidate who received the greatest number of votes (so long as they won a majority) became president, while the runner-up became vice president.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Twelfth Amendment would eventually replace this system, requiring electors to cast one vote for president and one vote for vice president, but this change did not take effect until 1804.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because of this, it is difficult to use modern-day terminology to describe the relationship among the candidates in this election.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington is generally held by historians to have run unopposed.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Indeed, the incumbent president enjoyed bipartisan support and received one vote from every elector.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The choice for vice president was more divisive.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Federalist Party threw its support behind the incumbent vice president, John Adams of Massachusetts, while the Democratic-Republican Party backed the candidacy of New York Governor George Clinton.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Because few doubted that Washington would receive the greatest number of votes, Adams and Clinton were effectively competing for the vice presidency; under the letter of the law, however, they were technically candidates for president competing against Washington.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Born out of the Anti-Federalist faction that had opposed the Constitution in 1788, the Democratic-Republican Party was the main opposition to the agenda of Treasury Secretary Alexander Hamilton.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] They had no chance of unseating Washington, but hoped to win the vice presidency by defeating the incumbent, Adams.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Many Democratic-Republicans would have preferred to nominate Thomas Jefferson, their ideological leader and Washington's Secretary of State.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, this would have cost them the state of Virginia, as electors were not permitted to vote for two candidates from their home state and Washington was also a Virginian.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton, the Governor of New York and a former anti-Federalist leader, became the party's nominee after he won the backing of Jefferson and James Madison.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Clinton was from an electorally important swing state, and he convinced party leaders that he would be a stronger candidate than another New Yorker, Senator Aaron Burr.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] A group of Democratic-Republican leaders met in Philadelphia in October 1792 and selected Clinton as the party's vice presidential candidate.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Madison was at first a Federalist until he opposed the establishment of Hamilton's First Bank of the United States in 1791.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] He formed the Democratic-Republican Party along with Anti-Federalist Thomas Jefferson in 1792.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The elections of 1792 were the first ones in the United States to be contested on anything resembling a partisan basis.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In most states, the congressional elections were recognized in some sense as a "struggle between the Treasury department and the republican interest," to use the words of Jefferson strategist John Beckley.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In New York, the race for governor was fought along these lines.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The candidates were Chief Justice John Jay, a Hamiltonian, and incumbent George Clinton, the party's vice presidential nominee.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Although Washington had been considering retiring, both sides encouraged him to remain in office to bridge factional differences.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was supported by practically all sides throughout his presidency and gained more popularity with the passage of the Bill of Rights.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] However, the Democratic-Republicans and the Federalists contested the vice-presidency, with incumbent John Adams as the Federalist nominee and George Clinton as the Democratic-Republican nominee.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Federalists attacked Clinton for his past association with the anti-Federalists.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Congress counted the electoral results on February 13, 1793, with John Adams opening and reading the votes in his role as President of the Senate.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Washington was re-elected unanimously, receiving one vote from each of the 132 participating electors.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received votes from 77 electors and Clinton 50; the four electors from Kentucky voted for Thomas Jefferson, and one South Carolina elector voted for Aaron Burr.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The distribution of the electoral vote between the four runners-up showed a high degree of party discipline, with only two electors voting contrary to the majority in their state.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Adams received the support of New England, South Carolina, and the Mid-Atlantic states (excepting New York), while Clinton carried New York and most of the South.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Nine of the 15 states eligible to choose representatives to the electoral college did so by a vote of the state legislature; the remaining six employed some form of popular vote.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of these, complete returns from Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, and Pennsylvania survive; surviving returns from Virginia are incomplete, and popular vote records from Kentucky are not known to exist.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Of the states with complete returns, only Pennsylvania saw real partisan competition; a Federalist electoral slate pledged to Washington and Adams was selected, although one elector voted for Washington and Clinton.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] At the time, party organizations were still in their infancy, and the partisan allegiance of the candidates was not always evident: it is therefore difficult to say whether the Pennsylvania vote for Clinton was an instance of a faithless elector, or an elector voting as pledged.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Elections in this period were vastly different from modern day presidential elections.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The actual presidential candidates were rarely mentioned on tickets and voters were voting for particular electors who were pledged to a particular candidate.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] There was sometimes confusion as to who the particular elector was actually pledged to.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Results are reported as the highest result for an elector for any given faction.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] For example, if three Federalist electors received 100, 50, and 25 votes, Federalist electors would be recorded as having 100 votes.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Confusion surrounding the way results are reported may lead to discrepancies between the sum of all state results and national results.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In Massachusetts, the best performing elector candidate for the Eastern District, Thomas Rice, was not selected by the Massachusetts General Court to be an elector.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Rice was a Federalist and his returns have been included into the state total below instead of the second best performing elector candidate.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The totals for Kentucky, Pennsylvania, and Virginia appear to be incomplete.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] In several states candidates of unknown affiliation received votes.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The states chose 135 electors, out of whom 132 cast ballots.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] (Two electors from Maryland and one from Vermont were absent and did not vote.) As per the terms of the unamended constitution, each elector was permitted two votes for president, with a majority of "the whole number of electors appointed" necessary to elect a president.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] Each of the participating electors cast one vote for Washington, who was elected president.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The electors were split on their second choice: Adams received 77 votes to Clinton's 50, enough to secure a second-place finish behind Washington and the vice presidency.
[src:1792-united-states-presidential-election-in-south-carolina/1792-united-states-presidential-election] The Constitution, in Article II, Section 1, provided that the state legislatures should decide the manner in which their Electors were chosen.
